in action, contributing to insulin resistance. It is often elevated in obesity and type 2 diabetes, correlating with decreased insulin sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisfatin\u003C/strong\u003E is an adipokine that has been associated with insulin-mimetic effects, potentially enhancing insulin action, although its role is complex and not fully understood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdiponectin\u003C/strong\u003E is an adipokine that enhances insulin sensitivity and is typically decreased in obesity and type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeptin\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily involved in regulating energy balance and appetite, but it also has roles in modulating insulin sensitivity, generally promoting insulin action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResistin\u003C/strong\u003E is another adipokine that has been implicated in insulin resistance, but its role is less clearly defined compared to retinol binding protein 4.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adipokines are proteins secreted by adipose tissue that can influence insulin sensitivity.","Retinol binding protein 4 is known to negatively regulate insulin action, contributing to insulin resistance.","Visfatin is an adipokine that has been associated with insulin-mimetic effects, potentially enhancing insulin action."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. doi: 10.1042/EBC20190041. PMID: 32830223; PMCID: PMC7545035","Austin J, Marks D. Hormonal regulators of appetite. Int J Pediatr Endocrinol. 2009;2009:141753. doi: 10.1155/2009/141753. Epub 2008 Dec 3. PMID: 19946401; PMCID: PMC2777281","Hernando-Redondo J, Toloba A, Benaiges D, Salas-Salvad\u00f3 J, Mart\u00ednez-Gonzalez MA, Co